――The battle between the Eighth Moguro Hagane and the old and new Nineth Madelyn Eschart and Balleroy Temeglyph continues to rage on beside the Crystal Palace.

The extraordinary battle that unfolds within the immediate vicinity is a clash between a giant humanoid city wall and a cloud-clad dragon, and the addition of the Empire's most powerful flying dragon rider is a fierce battle that will go down in the history of the Empire.

The roar and rumbling of the earth are the very screams of the Vollachian Empire, and the water flowing out of the destroyed reservoirs is a muddy stream that flows into the imperial capital.

The imperial city of Lupugana ――or rather, the Sacred Vollachian Empire itself was in the midst of an unprecedented upheaval that foreshadowed its destruction.

And yet, despite the circumstances――,

???: [Your Excellency or Your Excellency? Either way, the Great Disaster is coming. Please join me in resisting this Great Disaster!"

The "Stargazer," with his arms outstretched and a broad smile on his face, not looking at the crumbling streets of the Imperial Capital, is more than out of place; it is like a nightmare, easily trampling on the understanding of ordinary people.

But alas. The one who was confronted with the Stargazer's eccentric smile was the one who was the last person in this empire who was allowed to be ordinary.

???: [――――]

For a moment, Abel glanced behind the curtain at the miracle that saved his life.

What saved Abel from falling from a great height was a cloth stretched across where he had fallen, an improvised cushioning material gathered from the rooms of the Crystal Palace and the surrounding buildings.

The mechanism that saved the day was understandable. The question is why it was prepared.

One cannot prepare like this unless one ――no, unless one knows that Abel is going to fall.

Abel: [How much did you know!]

The moment he reached such a conclusion, Abel's outstretched hand grabbed the smiling Ubilk by the chest. He pulls him to his feet forcefully, and Ubilk bellows, "oh, oh, oh," and his eyes widen.

Face to face, directly in front of him, Abel relentlessly stared at the Ubilk, and

Abel: [Chisha's plan… No, that is not it. How far in advance did you know whose death would bring about the Great Disaster? You knew that my death and――]

Ubilk: [Yes, I said this. ――Vincent Vollachia's death will be the beginning of the Great Disaster that will bring ruin to the Empire.]

Staring at him from within breathing distance, but Ubilk's relaxed demeanor does not falter. Perhaps it is not so much composure. Rather, it is a different kind of disgusting anticipation or exuberance.

In fact, Ubilk is in high spirits. At last, the opportunity they have been waiting for has arrived.

But――,

Abel: [I am Vincent Vollachia.]

Ubilk: [No, no! Your Excellency! That is wrong. That is nooot~ true. I will say it out loud; it is not the same, Your Excellency.]

Abel: [――――]

Ubilk: [General First-Class Chisha Gold has unquestionably fulfilled the role of Vincent Vollachia. His Excellency himself, of all people, has made it possible for General Chisha Gold to do so.]

Abel: [I…]

It was not for this purpose that he kept Chisha Gold by his side.

He believed that when the Great Disaster came, he needed someone with the ability to take charge of everything within the Empire in place of the helpless emperor who could not be there.

Collaborating together with a worthy successor to the throne after his own death, one who will protect the Empire from destruction.

Abel: [Why did you take part in this plan?]

Ubilk: [what's that?]

Abel: [As a Stargazer, you are only interested in the fulfillment and implementation of your Commandment. Then if you wanted to ensure that the Great Disaster would happen, you should have used my life. Why did you decide to go along with Chisha's uncertain plans? It is nonsensical.]

A Stargazer is a commandment's puppet in human form.

No matter how much they may pretend to be likable or accommodating, what lies inside is nothing but an obsession with their commandment and a fanatical desire to fulfill it.

Their priorities should have been clear. So why did they side with Chisha's plan?

Abel: [Why? Answer me.]

Ubilk: [Ummm~, I think His Excellency would be offended if I were to say it.]

Abel: [Speak.]

Ubilk: [Well, it doesn't matter whether it's His Excellency himself or General First-Class Chisha. If it happened, good; if it didn't, bad. If Chisha dies in the guise of His Excellency, and there is no Great Disaster, then I will send His Excellency himself to…"

Abel: [――. So then, this situation is what you expected?]

When Ubilk stuck out his tongue in a mischievous manner, Abel quietly understood. At the same time, he understood that talking to Ubilk any further would not help.

Releasing his grip on his chest, Abel slowly turns to see, reflected in his vision through the Oni mask, several figures holding the edge of the cloth that saved Abel.

All of these faces have never been seen at the Crystal Palace before but――,

Abel: [Are these your people, too?]

Ubilk: [There isn't enough of us to call it a faction, though, is there?]

Shrugging his shoulders, Ubilk spins around and spreads his arms in front of his peers. The crowd of roughly a dozen people, young and old, male and female, presumably Stargazers just like him.

Less is more, although the Observers' pawns left their existence unacknowledged because of the uncertainty of how they are chosen.

Ubilk: [As I said, we are moving according to the commandment. What will His Excellency do?]

Abel: [I will――]

Pondering what to do, Abel tries to put his thoughts across his tongue.

However, in the process of responding to Ubilk, the ground was shaken by a loud impact, and a part of Moguro's body fell noisily some distance away from Abel and the others.

The battle was still raging, but since it was two against one, Moguro's disadvantage was undeniable.

The resurrection of the supposedly dead Balleroy Temeglyph and his beloved dragon.

The worst possibility one could deduce from this is that it is just not limited to them.

Ubilk: [The turmoil in the Imperial Capital and the crisis in the Empire, events that defy reason, are truly a sign of the Great Disaster.]

Ubilk cocks his chin to indicate to the sky as Abel shields his face from the flying dust.

The resurrected dead and dragons ran amok, foretelling mounting damage that would probably not end there.

Ubilk: [The Witch of the Kingdom, The Night Weeping of the City States, The Collapse of the Holy Kingdom, and The Great Disaster of the Empire… the four catastrophes that will destroy the world, the time is approaching. Even at this moment.]

Abel: [――――]

Ubilk: [Oh, and Your Excellency, this is just my personal opinion.]

Ubilk deliberately clapped his hands as he said something he had failed to mention. Then the Stargazer pointed overhead to Moguro's battle ――no, it was to something else.

Ubilk pointed not to the battle, but to the throne room with a large hole in it in the Crystal Palace, which was shaken in the aftermath of the fierce battle.

Ubilk: [Why did I cooperate with General First-Class Chisha's scheme? I am sincere in saying that it could have gone either way, but I thought that the probability was higher with… Your Excellency.]

Brazenly laughing, Ubilk lowers the hand that pointed to the crystal palace and, in the same motion, pointed it at Abel.

Ubilk: [My priority is the fulfillment of my commandment. My goal is to stop the Great Disaster from happening and the destruction it will bring. ――I have not wavered in my priority.]

A Stargazer is a living puppet obsessed with the realization and fulfillment of their commandment, trapped in their purpose.

That perception remains the same. Without changing that perception, Ubilk presents the reasons for his actions, the rationale for his choices, and the future he seeks.

He said that Abel was his priority in order to save the Vollachian Empire from the Great Disaster.

Abel: [――Chisha Gold, you were.]

In those eyes that had lost their color, what kind of future, what kind of expectations, did he draw in his black eyes, which he had imbued with the color of Vincent Vollachia

Why didn't he understand that words like hope and dreams are just a silly escape from reality?

Ubilk: [――Oh?]

An unexpected explosion roared in Abel's ears as he put his hand to his face and grabbed the cheek of his demon mask. Ubilk let out a silly voice in response, then a heavy sound fell to their side.

When Abel looked, something had fallen onto the cloth that had caught him earlier. However, unlike him, the cloth was not stretched to help, and did not play a role as cushioning material.

However――,

Goz: [You were correct that this cloth was laid out! Chancellor Berstetz! Are you alive!]

Berstetz?: [That took a toll on this old body, but somehow I... mm.]

Shaking off the cloth covering them, a large man with a naked upper body and a white-haired old man who was carried in his arms emerged from under the cloth.

Both of them looked familiar, and he never thought he would run into them here.

Ubilk: [Oh~, it's General Goz, isn't it? And Chancellor Berstetz is safe.]

Berstetz: [You are the one who ran away, but you're still here…]

Goz: [You! You're the Stargazer who told unnecessary things to General Chisha and Prime minister Berstetz! Because of you, his Excellency…his Excellency is…!!]

Overhead, a large man――Goz Ralfon, who had apparently jumped down from a large hole in the crystal palace, approached Ubilk with Berstetz, the Prime Minister, in his arms.

Now that he knew what Chisha was trying to do, he thought Goz was not killed, but how is it that he appeared here in this state as a result of the events that took place?

How much did Berstetz communicate with Chisha?

Goz: [The turmoil in the Imperial City and everything else! This is all caused by your schemes! You should die and apologize!]

Ubilk: [Wait wait~ a minute, please! I didn't do anything major, I didn't have anything to do with what happened to Goz! Because, you see, from a commandment point of view, Goz is not someone to worry about.]

Goz: [You, you bastard!]

Ubilk, with his superfluous talk, increasingly incurred Goz's wrath. Berstetz writhed painfully, as if Goz had forgotten that he was holding him.

Moreover, the changes in this situation did not stop there――,

Cecilus: [Wow!? The closer I get and see, the more mysterious it is! I run after the dragon that ignored me, and I find that my substitute opponent is a big doll! Sure, it may look good, but I don't think it's capable of acting as my substitute!]

Abel: [――――]

Just when he heard a yapping, high-pitched voice, the next moment the owner of the voice appeared with a tremendous wind at his back and a cloud of dust.

While he moved on the soles of his zori, he looked up at the sky with his hands forming a shelter, a boy with blue hair and kimono,  who had arrived without being called ――Everyone's eyes widen at the sight of his raucous demeanor, his words, actions, and above all else, the way he looked, a mere miniature version of a familiar figure.

Goz: [Ce, Cecilus Segmunt――!?]

Cecilus: [Huh? Did you call me just now? Well, I’m embarrassed that I did something that would spread my name with such lightning speed. To be honest, I thought the best moment was when I cut down that dragon, but I hate my degree of stardom!]

Goz: [...No doubt, it’s General First Class Cecilus!

The boy, who was watching the battle between Moguro and the “Cloud Dragon”, turned around and uttered those words with an unmistakably unique sense of distance.

There was Cecilus Segmunt, the strongest of the Nine Divine Generals and the First, who stood at the peak of the Vollachian Empire's military might, in a very young state.

He was just about this age when Abel first picked up Cecilus as a subordinate and took him under his wing. Since then,his mind aside, his body should have grown up.

Abel: [That's why you're so small… I can only believe it's Olbart Dunkelkenn's work, but if that's the case.]

Olbart’s behavior, when they met at the Demon City of Chaosflame, was illogical.

Olbart was, someway or another, unaware of the fact that Chisha had been masquerading as the Emperor. But supposing that Olbart was employing the same technique he had utilized on Natsuki Subaru, Medium, and Al, with Cecilus as the target, he could not help but cast doubts on the actions taken.

Why would the Emperor himself have Cecilus infantilized, he wondered.

A logical explanation for it seemed improbable. Cecilus had gone without being corrected for over a decade till this point. Right now, nothing could shackle him down.

In other words――,

???: [You're way too light-footed for a pipsqueak, aren't you? Can’t believe someone’s getting such a large lead on me, I'm really starting to feel my body’s deteriorated.]

Immediately after the thought crossed his mind, a petite shinobi―― Olbart Dunkelkenn, made his appearance right there and then. He had supposedly been entrusted with the defense of a bastion of the Imperial Capital, yet he had abandoned that role, returning to the Crystal Palace.

When it came to the reason as to why had Olbart, the shinobi head honcho, done such a thing,

Cecilus: [Huh, I thought I’d shaken you off, but I actually didn’t? That's great, old man! Still wanting a stage role even at that age, I kneel! Bravo!]

Olbart: [So loud. Ya forgot stuff altogether, haven’t ya?]

Cecilus: [Forgot stuff? Well, I got no idea what you’re talking about though.]

Olbart: [If I didn't do it and Ceci’s small, it’s got to have been that arse’s fault, Chesshy's. Though I like to steal others’ skills, I don't like it when they steal mine.]

Cecilus: [Ahahahaha, that's an amazingly selfish complaint! I don’t dislike it, rather, I quite like it.]

The old man, his lips curved in dissatisfaction, was laughed at by the much younger Cecilus, who was barely taller than him.

The Stargazer, Ubilk, was still being pressed for an answer by Goz, while Berstetz had been stolen of his freedom, being carried by his brawny arms, his mind more focused on whether the consequences of the still-raging battle between Moguro, the Cloud Dragon, and the resuscitated Balleroy were about to befall him.

Abel: […Just, what is this?]

One after the other, people had gathered at this place.

The majority of the Nine Divine Generals of the Vollachian Empire had come to this location, he came to realize.

Had this, too, been instigated by Chisha?

Vincent Vollachia had been able to do it, so how far had Chisha Gold gone beyond the former’s calculations, having been trained to be perform the same deeds?

He given his own life to keep Abel alive, and what was to come after――.

Chesha: [――My apologies, but I am afraid I would not.]

Abel: [――――]

Once upon a time, faced with a query from Vincent Abellux, Chisha Gold had replied thus.

Upon being asked if he was willing to die for him, he had returned the frank answer that he would not.

Then, the one for whom Chisha had laid down his life, was not Vincent Abellux.

Certainly, it had not been for Abel’s sake, in place of Vincent Vollachia. Chisha had not laid down his life for the ilks of a play on words――,

Abel: [――Heed my words! The Great Disaster is nigh! From here on, you shall abide by my command!]

Grinding his molars together, Abel lifted his face, leaped atop the rubble, turned around. Then viewing the entirety of the ensemble present, he thus asserted for all to listen.

Upon Abel's proclamation, each and all of those acting in selfish ways observed him.

At that moment, with the exception of Ubilk and Berstetz, who were in the know, the eyes of everyone, Divine Generals, included, had the utmost doubt flash across their eyes―― Just who in the world is this man?

Taking that in, Abel reached for the oni mask upon himself, seizing its cheek. In his last moments, Chisha had covered Abel with what the latter had removed. And with that, he had displayed his own real face.

And finally――,

Abel: [I am your Emperor, Vincent Vollachia. ――The alpha, of the Sword Wolves of the Empire.]
